---
description: Security rules — always applied across frontend and backend
alwaysApply: true
---

# Security non-negotiables

- Never render user-generated content via `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` without
  passing it through `DOMPurify` first. If you don't need rich text
  rendering, use plain `{content}` JSX interpolation and skip the sanitizer
  entirely — that's the simpler and safer default.
- Never put the access token in `localStorage` or `sessionStorage`. Access
  token lives in memory (a module-level variable or a React context), refresh
  token lives in an httpOnly Secure SameSite=Strict cookie set by the backend.
- Any `href` built from user input must be validated to start with `http://`
  or `https://` before rendering — reject `javascript:` and other schemes.
- All backend endpoints that mutate data must re-check authorization
  server-side, even if the frontend already hides the corresponding UI
  control. Client-side route/button hiding is UX, not security — see
  PROJECT_PLAN.md Phase 2 "Hunt for".
- CORS on the NestJS backend must whitelist the specific frontend origin, not
  `*`, since cookies (`credentials: true`) are in use.
- Never log JWTs, passwords, or refresh tokens, even at debug level.
- Passwords are hashed with `bcrypt` (or `argon2`) server-side — never
  compared or stored in plaintext, never sent back in any API response.
